Dear Ms. Caddell,
Thank you for your email of January 27 regarding use of grant funding in Montgomery County.

The Clean Water Management Trust Fund was created by the North Carolina General Assembly in 1996 to help restore degraded waters, protect unpolluted waters, and/or contribute toward a network of riparian buffers and greenways for environmental, educational, and recreational benefits. Since it’s creation, it has helped small towns and communities such as Troy and economically distressed counties like Montgomery keep their water supplies clean and safe.

CWMTF awarded two grants totaling $1.5 million to the Town of Troy to help reduce the amount of treated wastewater discharged into Badin Lake and Denson’s Creek in order to improve the water quality in both waterways.  The grants assisted the town in its effort to purchase the golf course at a bargain price as a way to protect the creek directly by establishing 30 to 50 feet of buffer zone around it.  The project added a mile to the town’s existing greenway system, providing residents with increased recreational opportunities while protecting water quality at the same time.  This initiative also received approximately $500,000 from the North Carolina Parks and Recreation Trust Fund.

In addition, the CWMTF funds assisted Troy in designing a plan to use the golf course itself to help reduce the amount of treated wastewater discharged into the lake and creek by using it for irrigation.  The town is has submitted a grant request in the 2009 CWMTF funding cycle for $1.4 million to actually construct the lines needed to carry the treated wastewater to the golf course, thereby reducing the amount of discharge into Denson’s Creek by 87 percent.  CWMTF’s Board of Trustees will review  that request later this year.

In total, CWMTF has awarded nine grants to the Town of Troy totaling $3.5 million dollars to protect water quality for its citizens.  Without clean water, the health and welfare of all of Montgomery County would be threatened.  Without clean water, there would be little economic incentive for business and industry in Montgomery County.  CWMTF has a legislative mandate to focus its grant resources in Tier One Economically Distressed Counties such as Montgomery and therefore the eight year working relationship CWMTF has with the Town of Troy represents a considerable effort to provide much needed assistance to one of the many areas of our state feeling the effects of our changing economy.

Again, thank you for expressing your concern.
Richard Rogers

Executive Director, Clean Water Management Trust Fund

