Dear Mr. David:

Thank you for your recent correspondence. The governor's office has asked that I respond to your e-mail.

I have learned that the bid process you are describing was being overseen by the state’s Ecosystem Enhancement Program as an effort to control invasive species on an important urban stream-restoration project in Durham’s Forest Hills Park.  The control of invasive species in the project is crucial to protecting North Carolina’s investment in water-quality improvement for the city of Durham’s Third Fork Creek and the Cape  Fear River basin.

The bid process for the contract in question, one of hundreds of EEP projects that DENR has outsourced to the private sector in the past six years, was conducted under procedures outlined in the State Construction Manual (<http://www.nc-sco.com/Manual/Chapter400%20-%20Bidding%20and%20Contracts.pdf>http://www.nc-sco.com/Manual/Chapter400%20-%20Bidding%20and%20Contracts.pdf).  The three representatives you identified from EEP were the site’s project manager, EEP’s design/construction supervisor and a water-resources engineer who focuses on the long-term monitoring of the project.  It is important to point out that the Forest Hills Park work is a pilot project for EEP's approach to dealing with invasive-plant removal statewide in its stream- and wetland-restoration projects, and all of the EEP staff on hand for this bid opening will be involved in similar efforts across the state.

While I regret that you were not pleased with the results of the bidding process, please be assured that normal procedures were followed and that the contract was awarded to the lowest responsible bidder, Invasive Plant Control Inc.  The company is based in Tennessee, but the work was performed by an employee who lives in the Triangle area.  The work was completed on time, for the bid price and to the satisfaction of EEP.

I hope this information clarifies this situation.

Sincerely,

