Dear Governor,



My name is Roc Sansotta. I have houses on Seagull Drive since 1988.  I have never asked the town or state or county for a penny to protect these houses.  My interest is to protect my investment.  When I bought these houses I was told the sandbags were for my protection.  As I signed to buy a Nor’easter hit and I lost 15 feet of driveway and didn’t know what I had gotten myself into. Now the CRC and CAMA has ordered me to take the sandbags out !!!!



It has been a constant struggle keeping these houses rentable. These houses all bring in money to the state, county and town.  I wonder why I can’t be left alone.  There are around 150 other homeowners in the same position.  Two people in the middle of my street have a $275,000 and a $300,000 mortgages and most others have large mortgages as well.  The only answer the town has given us is to give the town the houses and then pay $27,000 for them to be torn down.  I am sure neither the commissioners nor the Mayor would do this why would you ask the public to do this?



Flood insurance pays only if the house falls into the ocean.  My houses are fully booked for the entire season.  I reiterate that this is a lot of property tax and sales tax money that would go to the state, county and town.  Why would you not want to receive this money with the economy as it is now? 



Kaiser Chaffon was in this situation a few years ago with a $175,000 mortgage. He wasn’t allowed to repair his sandbags and it wiped out his septic tank.  The town then condemned his house and it was not allowed to become operational.  The town tore it down and put a judgment against him for $27,000+.  Then the bank put a judgment against him for his $175,000 mortgage and put a hold on all of his checking accounts in North Carolina , New Jersey , Arizona , etc.  A lien was put against all his properties instate and out of state.  This effectively ruined him because he wasn’t allowed to protect his property with sandbags



Bob Whetstine had his bags removed because of fear of a similar letter and it wiped out his septic tank. The town ordered his house to be torn down.  He succumbed to the request and then had to pay many thousands of dollars for it to be torn down.  He lost the house and the income from it.   His actions started a devastating chain of events on Nansemond Street .  After the first storm the house behind his became condemned as well as the house north of his house and the house behind that one.  The house north of that one was condemned as well.  Also the house south of his house and the house behind that house became condemned.  To this date all those houses are still condemned.



If  I pull my sandbags protecting my houses on Seagull Drive , the road will be washed out, the town’s water lines broken and the houses behind will become condemned after the first storm hits.  This will cause an out of control wildfire that will cost much needed revenue to the owners of these houses also to the state the county and the town. Let us keep and repair sandbags until we get beach nourishment.




